Citation.sTitle: Solubility of N-tert-Butylbenzothiazole-2-sulfenamide in Several Pure and Binary Solvents
Citation.sAbstract: The solubility of N-tert-butylbenzothiazole-2-sulphenamide (TBBS) in six pure solvents (methanol, ethanol, toluene, 2-propanol, 1-butanol and tert-butylamine) and three binary solvents (methanol + water, ethanol + water and tert-butylamine + water) was measured in the temperature range between 273.2 K and 313.2 K using a gravimetric determination at pressure of 0.101 MPa. The initial mole fraction of methanol, ethanol or tert-butylamine in binary solvents was in the range from 0.4 to 1.0. The experimental data shows that the solubility of TBBS increases with the increasing temperature in both pure and binary solvents. The solubility of TBBS in the six pure solvents has the following sequence: x1, tert-butylamine greater than x1, toluene greater than x1, 1-butanol greater than x1, ethanol greater than x1, 2-propanol greater than x1, methanol. The experimental solubility data can be well correlated by four thermodynamic models: the modified Apelblat equation, h equation, CNIBS/R-K model and NRTL model. The solubility of TBBS in tert-butylamine at a high temperature range from 318.2 K to 343.2 K at pressure from 0.156 MPa to 0.213 MPa was also determined using an approach based on turbidity measurement.
